The ClassIds are used to identify Object child classes through the Object::Is virtual method.

detaileddescription.para: Each Object child class has to have its own id which is stored in the member variable m_classId. Base classes (e.g., LayerElement) that are never instanciated have boundary ids used for checking if an Object is child of a base class. See for example Object::IsLayerElement.

briefdescription.para: The InterfaceIds are used to identify Interface child classes through the Interface::IsInterface virtual method.

detaileddescription.para: Each Interface child class has to have its own id and has to override the IsInterface() method.

briefdescription.para: This is the alternate way for representing map of maps.

detaileddescription.para: With this solution, we can easily have different types of key (attribute) at each level. We could mix int, string, or even MEI data_* types. The drawback is that a type has to be defined at each level. Also see Doc::PrepareData for an example.
